      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

I think there is a possible=C2=A0endgame now for the Sculptor Capital Manag=
ement Inc. situation?
  [1]
=C2=A0It goes like this:
=09Right now, Sculptor has a deal to sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp. for=
 $11.15 per share. And it has a competing bid from a group of hedge fund ma=
nagers led by Boaz Weinstein, who want to buy Sculptor for something like $=
13 per share. Sculptor=E2=80=99s board of directors=C2=A0has, so far, refus=
ed to chuck the Rithm deal for Weinstein. Presumably the board hoped that R=
ithm would raise its price to something closer to $13.=09But after thinking=
 about it for a bit, Rithm  declined to raise its price.=09Sculptor could s=
till ask its shareholders to vote to approve the Rithm deal. Last Thursday,=
 it filed another draft proxy statement for that vote, recommending that sh=
areholders vote for the $11.15 Rithm deal.=09Will they,=C2=A0though? Sculpt=
or=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $11.97. If you think that $11.15 is =
a good price, you should sell your stock, today, to someone who doesn=E2=80=
=99t. Anyone who owns the stock by the time of the shareholder vote is goin=
g to want more than $11.15.
  [2]
=C2=A0=09Meanwhile, Weinstein can=E2=80=99t do anything to=C2=A0force Sculp=
tor=E2=80=99s board to deal with him. In particular, as part of Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s original efforts to auction itself last year, Weinstein signed a no=
ndisclosure agreement with a standstill clause barring him from making publ=
ic offers to buy Sculptor. Traditionally the way to bypass the board is wit=
h a tender offer: You just go out and offer to buy everyone=E2=80=99s share=
s for cash, and if more than half of the shareholders tender=C2=A0then you =
control the company.
  [3]
=C2=A0But Weinstein can=E2=80=99t do that, because of his NDA.=09But Weinst=
ein=E2=80=99s=C2=A0standstill expires on Dec. 22. It seems unlikely that Sc=
ulptor will be able to push through the Rithm deal before that. (There is n=
o date set yet for the shareholder vote.)=C2=A0Which means that Weinstein m=
ight be able to launch a tender offer and buy the company.

This is not an=C2=A0optimal=C2=A0endgame. Weinstein would much rather come =
to a negotiated deal with Sculptor before December. For one thing, it would=
 be faster. For another thing, tendering blindly to buy Sculptor without re=
aching any agreement with the board or management is=C2=A0risky. Weinstein =
is trying to buy=C2=A0an asset manager with some $30 billion or so of asset=
s under management, much of it not very locked up, and that=E2=80=99s a bet=
ter deal if the clients plan to stick around. If he can talk to Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s management, meet with the biggest clients, hear their concerns and =
reassure them, that reduces the risk that he=E2=80=99ll end up buying Sculp=
tor and getting nothing.
  [4]
 There are regulatory and business risks to buying an asset manager with a =
tender offer, and it would not be anyone=E2=80=99s first choice.
  [5]

But Weinstein probably=C2=A0has the ability to force that endgame, which me=
ans that he is in a better negotiating position to get the deal he wants. H=
e can go to Sculptor and say:
=09Talk to me now, let me meet with your biggest clients and reassure them,=
 and if all goes well we can sign a merger agreement at $13 per share in ca=
sh.=09If you don=E2=80=99t, you=E2=80=99re still not going to get the Rithm=
 deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0shareholders will vote no =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I=E2=80=
=99ll do a tender offer in December. But it won=E2=80=99t be for $13. The d=
elay and annoyance will cost=C2=A0your shareholders=C2=A0something, because=
 I=E2=80=99ll only pay $12.25 in the tender. I=E2=80=99ll still get the com=
pany =E2=80=94=C2=A0$12.25 is more than $11.15, and more than it=E2=80=99ll=
 be worth with no deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I=E2=80=99ll pay less than I woul=
d if you negotiate now.

So that=E2=80=99s what he did. Last Thursday=E2=80=99s  proxy statement lay=
s out Weinstein=E2=80=99s ask: He offered to sign an agreement to buy Sculp=
tor for $12.76 per share, conditional on 40% of its hedge-fund clients cons=
enting to the change in management, but he also offered some sweeteners. Fo=
r one thing, if Sculptor lets him talk to its estranged founder, Dan Och, a=
nd the other former executive managing directors who still own a big chunk =
of Sculptor, he might raise his bid:
The September 30 Proposal reiterated the Consortium=E2=80=99s request to co=
ntact the Former EMD Group and indicated that, depending on the outcome of =
its discussions and the Former EMD Group=E2=80=99s willingness to enter int=
o a rollover, the Consortium would consider increasing its price to $13.00 =
per share of Class A Common Stock.=C2=A0
For another thing, if Sculptor lets him talk to its=C2=A0clients, he might =
lower the client consent condition:
The Consortium noted that it may have the ability to further lower or elimi=
nate the 40% client run-rate consent threshold for the Company=E2=80=99s Mu=
lti-Strategy and Opportunistic Credit business lines if it were permitted t=
o speak with certain of the Company=E2=80=99s clients that comprise a subst=
antial portion of the revenue associated with those strategies.
So if Sculptor negotiates with Weinstein and all goes well, it could get a =
deal at $13 per share without much conditionality. (Of course, all might no=
t go well: If Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is really convinced that all of its =
big clients will say no to Weinstein, letting him talk to them will not get=
 him to pay $13. It would get him to go away, though! Which also has some v=
alue.)
But the proxy also lays out Weinstein=E2=80=99s threat about what will happ=
en if the board doesn=E2=80=99t negotiate:
The Consortium further stated an intention to initiate a cash tender offer =
for a reduced price of $12.25 per share of Class A Common Stock following t=
he expiration of Bidder J=E2=80=99s standstill on December 22, 2023, if the=
 Company Stockholders had not approved the Merger Proposal prior to such ti=
me.
It=E2=80=99s a good threat: $12.25 is less than $13 (or $12.76), but more t=
han $11.15. If you are a Sculptor shareholder, asked to approve the $11.15 =
Rithm deal, you will be tempted to say no and hold out for the $12.25 Weins=
tein tender.
  [6]
=C2=A0Which means there=E2=80=99s a good chance that the Rithm deal will fa=
il and Weinstein will end up buying the company at $12.25. Which means that=
, for the board, it would be better to get $13 from Weinstein now than $12.=
25 from him later.=C2=A0
Meanwhile the board=C2=A0was=C2=A0working on a process in which:
=09Rithm would raise its price, maybe not to $12.76 but to something closer=
 than $11.15,
  [7]
=C2=A0and=09in exchange, Och and the other former executives would agree to=
 support the Rithm deal, further freezing out Weinstein.
  [8]



That would have been a good outcome for the board: They get the deal they a=
re comfortable with, and that they think clients will be comfortable with, =
but at a price that is good enough=C2=A0for shareholders. But that didn=E2=
=80=99t work out, mostly because Weinstein raised his bid and Och decided W=
einstein was better than Rithm, so Rithm =E2=80=9Cwas not prepared to (1) e=
nter into the amended Merger Agreement without the Former EMD Support or (2=
) offer any other improvements to the terms and conditions of the Merger Ag=
reement or the Transactions.=E2=80=9D
And so Sculptor=E2=80=99s board, which has been pretty tough about ignoring=
 Weinstein so far, has opened the door a crack. It=E2=80=99s writing a merg=
er agreement to send to Weinstein:
So as not to lose time while the Special Committee was evaluating whether t=
o make a Superior=C2=A0Proposal Determination, the Special Committee author=
ized Latham & Watkins to request Rithm=E2=80=99s consent to engage with the=
 Consortium and instructed Latham & Watkins to begin preparing revised draf=
t definitive transaction documents to send to the Consortium that the Speci=
al Committee would be prepared to authorize at a price of $13.00 per share =
of Class A Common Stock.
And it=E2=80=99s not saying no:

The Special Committee determined to continue to evaluate the September 30 P=
roposal with its advisors and continue to engage with Rithm regarding poten=
tial improvements to the terms and conditions of the Merger Agreement and t=
he Transactions in parallel.
The Special Committee is continuing to evaluate the September 30 Proposal, =
as amended by the October 2 Letter, in consultation with its independent fi=
nancial and legal advisors and will make its recommendation to the Company=
=E2=80=99s Board of Directors and determine next steps in due course. Consi=
stent with its fiduciary duties, the Special Committee and the Company=E2=
=80=99s Board of Directors will determine the best path forward with the in=
terest of maximizing value for all Company Stockholders.

It seems like Weinstein has worn the board down enough that he might get hi=
s deal. Or, of course,  the board has worn Weinstein down enough that they =
might get $13 per share. Arguably this is a win for both of them.

