   =20
      Deposit duration
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a   lot around   here about two theories of banking.
=09Banks borrow short to lend long. Banks get their funding from deposits, =
which can be withdrawn at any time, and use it to buy long-term loans and b=
onds. This is risky. If interest rates go up, banks have to pay more for fu=
nding, while the value of their long-term assets goes down.=09Banks borrow =
long to lend long. Bank deposits=C2=A0can=C2=A0be withdrawn at any time, bu=
t=C2=A0they mostly=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t. Banks invest in long-term relations=
hips with customers, who deposit money and are not inclined to withdraw it.=
 And banks use that cheap long-term funding to buy long-term assets, and al=
so to invest in the things (branches, customer service,   Little League spo=
nsorship) that create the long-term relationships.

Theory 1, I have said, is the standard theory of modern capital markets; Th=
eory 2 is the traditional theory of=C2=A0banking. Theory 2 more or less des=
cribes how most banks mostly work; Theory 1 more or less describes why   Si=
licon Valley Bank failed this spring.
You could have intermediate theories. Theory 1 says that bank deposits are =
short-term, Theory 2 that they are long-term. Here is =E2=80=9C Deposit Con=
vexity, Monetary Policy, and Financial Stability,=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Emily Gr=
eenwald and=C2=A0Sam Schulhofer-Wohl of the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas=
=C2=A0and Joshua Younger of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, which arg=
ues that deposits are long-term, but become shorter-term as rates go up. Wh=
ich is exactly what you don=E2=80=99t want:
In principle, bank deposits can be withdrawn on demand. In practice, deposi=
tors tend to maintain stable balances for long periods, allowing banks to f=
und long-dated assets. Nevertheless, the cost of deposit funding influences=
 banks=E2=80=99 capacity for maturity transformation. Banks and researchers=
 conventionally model the response of deposit interest rates to market inte=
rest rates as constant, implying that deposits have nearly constant duratio=
n. Contrary to this standard assumption, we show empirically that the =E2=
=80=9Cbeta=E2=80=9D of deposit rates to market rates increases as market ra=
tes rise, causing the duration of deposits to fall. The amount of duration =
risk delivered to bank balance sheets via this channel from March 2022 to S=
eptember 2023 is comparable in magnitude to the amount of duration risk abs=
orbed by each of the several large-scale asset purchase programs the Federa=
l Reserve has undertaken since 2008. Dynamic betas present a significant ch=
allenge to bank portfolio hedgers by introducing large and dynamic risks th=
at are difficult to model and impractical to replicate on the asset side of=
 the balance sheet. As a result, deposit convexity amplifies monetary polic=
y transmission and increases financial fragility, mechanisms that recent ba=
nking stresses have highlighted.
Intuitively, banks match the duration of their assets (mortgages, Treasury =
bonds, etc.) to the duration of their liabilities (deposits, assuming that =
the deposits are pretty stable). As interest rates go up, the assets lose v=
alue: A 10-year Treasury bond with 3% interest is worth 100 cents on the do=
llar when rates are 3%, but only 85 cents when rates are 5%. But as interes=
t rates go up, the value to the bank of its deposit franchise should also g=
o up: Paying 0% on stable deposits is worth more when rates are 5% than whe=
n they are worth 3%. The books balance. Except that this is wrong, and in r=
eality=C2=A0the duration of the deposits goes down as rates go up.
Elsewhere in banking:

Banks globally reaped a $280 billion profit boost in 2022 thanks to rising =
rates, in the sector=E2=80=99s best performance since the 2008 global finan=
cial crisis, McKinsey & Co. said.
An unprecedented series of interest-rate increases by monetary authorities =
across the world has provided the biggest tailwind for the global banking i=
ndustry in over a decade. The bonanza has prompted several lenders to annou=
nce billions of dollars in share buybacks.

When Silicon Valley Bank failed, a lot of people asked, in effect, =E2=80=
=9Chow could they have been so stupid?=E2=80=9D The math was obvious: They =
had a bunch of long-term bonds funded with a bunch of short-term deposits; =
as rates went up, the bonds lost value and the deposits fled. A standard Th=
eory 1 sort of objection. And the answer was, roughly: =E2=80=9CActually ba=
nks usually benefit from rising rates, and SVB bought all those long-term b=
onds in part because it was worried about the risk of rates going=C2=A0down=
, which would crush its profitability.=E2=80=9D A standard Theory 2 type of=
 answer. Which was wrong about SVB, but right in general: The thing that bl=
ew up SVB and a handful of other US regional banks
  [9]
 was also =E2=80=9Cthe biggest tailwind for the global banking industry in =
over a decade.=E2=80=9D
It=E2=80=99s not just SVB though. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Katherine Doherty r=
eports:

For years, Brian Moynihan told investors his bank would be a big winner whe=
n interest rates eventually, finally, one day went up. Bank of America Corp=
. had built a massive deposit base that would allow profits to soar when th=
e Federal Reserve changed course.
Rates have indeed shot up =E2=80=94 and BofA is the biggest laggard among t=
he US banking giants. Its investments earn less than its closest rivals, an=
d the stock is the group=E2=80=99s worst performer by far.
In part, that=E2=80=99s because BofA piled hundreds of billions of dollars =
into long-dated Treasuries and mortgage bonds at low rates that prevailed d=
uring the pandemic. The decision is still the subject of finger-pointing wi=
thin the walls of the second-largest US bank, say people familiar with the =
matter, now that those holdings are showing huge paper losses and missing o=
ut on some of the best rates since 2007.

If your thesis is =E2=80=9Cwe have built a massive deposit base that will a=
llow profits to soar when the Fed changes course,=E2=80=9D your main risk i=
s that rates will stay low and profits won=E2=80=99t soar. You hedge that r=
isk by buying long-dated Treasuries: If rates go up, you lose money on your=
 Treasuries but you=E2=80=99re happy because of your deposit base; if they =
don=E2=80=99t, you make (relatively) a lot of money on the Treasuries to ti=
de you over. (Doherty: =E2=80=9CThe move was designed to help protect the b=
ank=E2=80=99s net interest margin if rates didn=E2=80=99t move or declined.=
=E2=80=9D) But if (1) everyone else doesn=E2=80=99t hedge that risk, and ke=
eps their money in short-term assets and (2) the Fed=C2=A0does=C2=A0rapidly=
 raise rates, then you will look comparatively bad.

 =20
   =20
      Closed-end muni fund duration
   =20
 =20

Outside of banking, meanwhile, Theory 1 is basically correct? That=E2=80=99=
s why people were so puzzled by SVB=E2=80=99s failure: Everywhere else in c=
apital markets, it is just obvious that if you borrow short-term to buy lon=
g-duration assets, and rates go up, you will lose money. Banks are special =
because their borrowing is technically short-term but really something else=
. But lots of other businesses are in this sort of maturity transformation =
business without that special advantage. The Wall Street Journal  reports t=
oday:

Some municipal-bond funds are suffering their worst stretch since the 2008-=
09 financial crisis, an acute example of how two years of rising interest r=
ates have slammed investors=E2=80=99 portfolios.
Closed-end municipal-bond funds have been particularly hard-hit because the=
y often use borrowed money to invest in fixed-rate, long-term bonds sold by=
 state and local governments. The leverage helps boost the returns from deb=
t that is ultrasafe, but pays relatively little interest.
That worked for much of the past decade until rates started rising. Now, sh=
ort-term borrowing is becoming more expensive while the market value of old=
er, lower-yielding bonds in the mutual funds is falling.=C2=A0

Yes right if you use $50 of your own money and $50 of borrowed money to buy=
 a $100=C2=A0bond=C2=A0that pays 2% interest, and your borrowing costs 0%, =
then you make a 4% return on your $50. If your borrowing costs 5% and the b=
ond=C2=A0still pays 2%, you lose money.

 =20
   =20
      Coin flips
   =20
 =20

We have   talked, several   times now, for reasons, about whether and how m=
uch you should bet on a coin flip with slightly positive expected value. On=
e claim about the Jane Street Capital internship program, which gave Sam Ba=
nkman-Fried his start in financial markets, is that =E2=80=9Ca=C2=A0Jane St=
reet intern had what amounted to a professional obligation to take any bet =
with a positive expected value,=E2=80=9D very much including a biased coin =
flip with 1% edge.
Well, bad news for Jane Street interns: That=E2=80=99s every coin flip. Her=
e is a new paper titled =E2=80=9CFair coins tend to land on the same side t=
hey started: Evidence from 350,757 Flips,=E2=80=9D by Franti=C5=A1ek Barto=
=C5=A1 and a surprisingly long list of co-authors:
Many people have flipped coins but few have stopped to ponder the statistic=
al and physical intricacies of the process. In a preregistered study we col=
lected 350,757 coin flips to test the counterintuitive prediction from a ph=
ysics model of human coin tossing developed by Persi Diaconis. The model as=
serts that when people flip an ordinary coin, it tends to land on the same =
side it started -- Diaconis estimated the probability of a same-side outcom=
e to be about 51%. Our data lend strong support to this precise prediction:=
 the coins landed on the same side more often than not,=C2=A0Pr(same side)=
=3D0.508, 95% credible interval (CI) [0.506,=C2=A00.509],=C2=A0BFsame-side =
bias=3D2364. Furthermore, the data revealed considerable between-people var=
iation in the degree of this same-side bias. Our data also confirmed the ge=
neric prediction that when people flip an ordinary coin -- with the initial=
 side-up randomly determined -- it is equally likely to land heads or tails=
:=C2=A0Pr(heads)=3D0.500, 95% CI [0.498, 0.502], BFheads-tails bias=3D0.183=
. Furthermore, this lack of heads-tails bias does not appear to vary across=
 coins. Our data therefore provide strong evidence that when some (but not =
all) people flip a fair coin, it tends to land on the same side it started.=
 Our data provide compelling statistical support for Diaconis' physics mode=
l of coin tossing.
Actually the list of co-authors is so long because they needed people to fl=
ip the coins. =E2=80=9CA group of 48 people (i.e., all but three of the co-=
authors) tossed coins of 46 different currencies =C3=97 denominations and o=
btained a total number of 350,757 coin flips,=E2=80=9D says the  paper. Aca=
demia is great.
The paper=C2=A0does=C2=A0not describe the technique=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Csome=
 (but not all) people=E2=80=9D use to flip a coin to cause it to land more =
often on the starting side. Nor are there diagrams.
  [10]
=C2=A0Nonetheless I assert:
=09There is probably a technique.=09It is probably learnable.=09If you get =
good at it you can probably get your probability up to, like, 55%.=09If you=
 have a Jane Street internship next summer you had better start practicing =
now.


