  [1] We have discussed this situation a lot around here. We first discusse=
d the Weinstein consortium bid  here, and the basic economics of it  here. =
We discussed Dan Och's interests  here, Sculptor=E2=80=99s board=E2=80=99s =
concerns  here and  here, and the most recent developments  here.


  [2] Except maybe Sculptor=E2=80=99s management, led by Chief Executive Of=
ficer Jimmy Levin, who have their own reasons for preferring Rithm, and who=
 have agreed to vote for the deal. But they own roughly one-fifth of the vo=
tes and can=E2=80=99t force the deal through on their own.


  [3] This is oversimplified, and in theory the board could use a  poison p=
ill to block him, but I think in this situation =E2=80=94 where they=E2=80=
=99ve agreed to sell to Rithm for $11.15 in cash =E2=80=94 it's tough to bl=
ock a higher tender.


  [4] Or, of course, if he meets with all the clients and they say =E2=80=
=9Cwe hate you and would pull our money immediately,=E2=80=9D then he knows=
 not to go through with the deal. In a tender he can=E2=80=99t really do th=
at; in a negotiated deal he can do due diligence before signing, and if the=
 diligence on this point is bad he can just not sign.


  [5] The proxy hints at these concerns: =E2=80=9CThe Special Committee fur=
ther noted that any proposed tender offer by the Consortium would be subjec=
t to U.S. tender offer rules, and it was unclear to the Special Committee h=
ow the Consortium would be able to secure required regulatory approvals and=
 client consents in connection with a tender offer made directly to the Com=
pany Stockholders. Following discussion, the Special Committee continued to=
 have significant concerns as to whether the Consortium Client Consent Cond=
ition could reasonably be expected to be satisfied, and therefore whether t=
he proposed transaction with the Consortium could reasonably be expected to=
 close.=E2=80=9D


  [6] To be clear: There is no $12.25 Weinstein tender. It=E2=80=99s just a=
 thing he said in a letter. If you are a Sculptor shareholder voting no on =
the Rithm deal, it=E2=80=99s because you think it is highly likely that Wei=
nstein will follow through with this, because you think he really wants the=
 company. But it is a risk. If you think he=E2=80=99s just pulling Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s leg, you should take the $11.15. (Or, I mean, sell your stock at=
 $11.97 now.) Pulling Sculptor=E2=80=99s leg would be *odd* behavior, but y=
ou can=E2=80=99t really rule it out. If Weinstein blows up the Rithm deal a=
nd then *doesn=E2=80=99t* buy Sculptor, then arguably he has crippled a com=
petitor. Plus there are weird personal dynamics here, and you can=E2=80=99t=
 put the odds of some sort of personal grudge motivation at zero.


  [7] As part of raising its price, Rithm also wanted a higher termination =
fee. This is reasonable, and the board was okay with it, but it is a bit od=
d. The board was willing to give Rithm a higher termination fee, to protect=
 its deal from being jumped by Weinstein, in exchange for Rithm raising its=
 price to *a price lower than Weinstein=E2=80=99s*. If Rithm had raised to =
$13.10, sure, give it a fully locked-up deal. But raising to $12.20, when t=
here=E2=80=99s a competing bid at $12.76 or so, does not really justify a h=
igher breakup fee. Anyway they never signed it so this is moot.


  [8] One other factor here is that Rithm=E2=80=99s deal still has a condit=
ion that 85% of clients have to consent. Given that the board keeps saying =
the Weinstein deal is too risky because it requires 80% of real-estate and =
collateralized-loan-obligation clients to consent, and 40% of hedge-fund cl=
ients, it is awkward that its preferred deal with Rithm requires 85%. The b=
oard can say that it is confident clients would consent to Rithm and not We=
instein, but it=E2=80=99s odd to have a double standard in the formal docum=
ent. It was trying to fix that in the revised Rithm deal: =E2=80=9CFollowin=
g a discussion, the Special Committee determined that it would ask Rithm to=
 eliminate the Rithm Client Consent Condition in the Merger Agreement. =E2=
=80=A6 On September 23, 2023, representatives of Citi informed representati=
ves of J.P. Morgan that assuming the Special Committee was otherwise prepar=
ed to agree to the other Proposed Amendments (and subject to receiving the =
Former EMD Support), Rithm would agree to remove the Rithm Client Consent C=
ondition in the Merger Agreement.=E2=80=9D But then they never signed the a=
mendment.


  [9] And =E2=80=A6  Credit Suisse Group AG? Indirectly?


  [10] There is, however, a table of the co-authors=E2=80=99 individual res=
ults, which range from 48.7% to an  astounding 60.1% (1,682 of 2,800, a 95%=
 confidence interval of 58.2% to 61.9%) of flips landing on the same side. =
Tianqi Peng of the University of Amsterdam could make a killing flipping co=
ins at Jane Street.


