<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks borrow short to lend long. Bank=
s get their funding from deposits, which can be withdrawn at any time, and =
use it to buy long-term loans and bonds. This is risky. If interest rates g=
o up, banks have to pay more for funding, while the value of their long-ter=
m assets goes down.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks borrow l=
ong to lend long. Bank deposits=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>be withdrawn at any =
time, but=C2=A0they mostly=C2=A0<em>aren=E2=80=99t</em>. Banks invest in lo=
ng-term relationships with customers, who deposit money and are not incline=
d to withdraw it. And banks use that cheap long-term funding to buy long-te=
rm assets, and also to invest in the things (branches, customer service, <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32995076.257419/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMDYvc21hbGw=
