 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">in ban=
king</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks globally reaped a $280 billion profit bo=
ost in 2022 thanks to rising rates, in the sector=E2=80=99s best performanc=
e since the 2008 global financial crisis, McKinsey &amp; Co. said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An unprecedented series of interest-rate incre=
ases by monetary authorities across the world has provided the biggest tail=
wind for the global banking industry in over a decade. The bonanza has prom=
pted several lenders to announce billions of dollars in share buybacks.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Silicon Valley Bank failed, a lot of peop=
le asked, in effect, =E2=80=9Chow could they have been so stupid?=E2=80=9D =
The math was obvious: They had a bunch of long-term bonds funded with a bun=
ch of short-term deposits; as rates went up, the bonds lost value and the d=
eposits fled. A standard Theory 1 sort of objection. And the answer was, ro=
ughly: =E2=80=9CActually banks usually benefit from rising rates, and SVB b=
ought all those long-term bonds in part because it was worried about the ri=
sk of rates going=C2=A0<em>down</em>, which would crush its profitability.=
=E2=80=9D A standard Theory 2 type of answer. Which was wrong about SVB, bu=
t right in general: The thing that blew up SVB and a handful of other US re=
gional banks<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a> was also =E2=80=9Cthe biggest tailwind for the global banking industry=
 in over a decade.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not just SVB though. Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32995076.2=
57419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDkvY=
m9mYS1zLXdyb25nLXdheS1yYXRlLWJsdW5kZXItbWFycy1tb3luaWhhbi1zLWdyb3d0aC1wbGVk=
Z2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBc4c640b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Katherine Doherty reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For years, Brian Moynihan told investors his b=
ank would be a big winner when interest rates eventually, finally, one day =
went up. Bank of America Corp. had built a massive deposit base that would =
allow profits to soar when the Federal Reserve changed course.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rates have indeed shot up =E2=80=94 and BofA i=
s the biggest laggard among the US banking giants. Its investments earn les=
s than its closest rivals, and the stock is the group=E2=80=99s worst perfo=
rmer by far.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In part, that=E2=80=99s because BofA piled hun=
dreds of billions of dollars into long-dated Treasuries and mortgage bonds =
at low rates that prevailed during the pandemic. The decision is still the =
subject of finger-pointing within the walls of the second-largest US bank, =
say people familiar with the matter, now that those holdings are showing hu=
ge paper losses and missing out on some of the best rates since 2007.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If your thesis is =E2=80=9Cwe have built a mas=
sive deposit base that will allow profits to soar when the Fed changes cour=
se,=E2=80=9D your main risk is that rates will stay low and profits won=E2=
=80=99t soar. You hedge that risk by buying long-dated Treasuries: If rates=
 go up, you lose money on your Treasuries but you=E2=80=99re happy because =
of your deposit base; if they don=E2=80=99t, you make (relatively) a lot of=
 money on the Treasuries to tide you over. (Doherty: =E2=80=9CThe move was =
designed to help protect the bank=E2=80=99s net interest margin if rates di=
dn=E2=80=99t move or declined.=E2=80=9D) But if (1) everyone else <em>doesn=
=E2=80=99t</em> hedge that risk, and keeps their money in short-term assets=
 and (2) the Fed=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>rapidly raise rates, then you will=
 look comparatively bad.</p>
